83/// Return the specified type promoted as it would be to pass though a va_arg
84/// area.
85static Type *getPromotedType(Type *Ty) {
86 if (IntegerType* ITy = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(Ty)) {
87 if (ITy->getBitWidth() < 32)
88 return Type::getInt32Ty(Ty->getContext());
89 }
90 return Ty;
91}

93/// Return a constant boolean vector that has true elements in all positions
94/// where the input constant data vector has an element with the sign bit set.
95static Constant *getNegativeIsTrueBoolVec(ConstantDataVector *V) {
96 SmallVector<Constant *, 32> BoolVec;
97 IntegerType *BoolTy = Type::getInt1Ty(V->getContext());
98 for (unsigned I = 0, E = V->getNumElements(); I != E; ++I) {
99 Constant *Elt = V->getElementAsConstant(I);
100 assert((isa<ConstantInt>(Elt) || isa<ConstantFP>(Elt)) &&
101 "Unexpected constant data vector element type");
102 bool Sign = V->getElementType()->isIntegerTy()
103 ? cast<ConstantInt>(Elt)->isNegative()
104 : cast<ConstantFP>(Elt)->isNegative();
105 BoolVec.push_back(ConstantInt::get(BoolTy, Sign));
106 }
107 return ConstantVector::get(BoolVec);
108}

110Instruction *InstCombiner::SimplifyAnyMemTransfer(AnyMemTransferInst *MI) {
111 unsigned DstAlign = getKnownAlignment(MI->getRawDest(), DL, MI, &AC, &DT);
112 unsigned CopyDstAlign = MI->getDestAlignment();
113 if (CopyDstAlign < DstAlign){
114 MI->setDestAlignment(DstAlign);
115 return MI;
116 }
117
118 unsigned SrcAlign = getKnownAlignment(MI->getRawSource(), DL, MI, &AC, &DT);
119 unsigned CopySrcAlign = MI->getSourceAlignment();
120 if (CopySrcAlign < SrcAlign) {
121 MI->setSourceAlignment(SrcAlign);
122 return MI;
123 }
124
125 // If we have a store to a location which is known constant, we can conclude
126 // that the store must be storing the constant value (else the memory
127 // wouldn't be constant), and this must be a noop.
128 if (AA->pointsToConstantMemory(MI->getDest())) {
129 // Set the size of the copy to 0, it will be deleted on the next iteration.
130 MI->setLength(Constant::getNullValue(MI->getLength()->getType()));
131 return MI;
132 }
133
134 // If MemCpyInst length is 1/2/4/8 bytes then replace memcpy with
135 // load/store.
136 ConstantInt *MemOpLength = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(MI->getLength());
137 if (!MemOpLength) return nullptr;
138
139 // Source and destination pointer types are always "i8*" for intrinsic. See
140 // if the size is something we can handle with a single primitive load/store.
141 // A single load+store correctly handles overlapping memory in the memmove
142 // case.
143 uint64_t Size = MemOpLength->getLimitedValue();
144 assert(Size && "0-sized memory transferring should be removed already.");
145
146 Type *CpyTy = nullptr;
147 if (Size > 8 || (Size&(Size-1))) {
148 // This heuristic is silly, because it prevents us from doing vector
149 // loads and stores. It also means that on CHERI we weren't optimising
150 // single-pointer copies. For now, special case pointer signed and aligned
151 // things for CHERI.
152 if (!DL.isFatPointer(200))
153 return nullptr; // If not 1/2/4/8 bytes, exit.
154 uint64_t PtrCpySize = DL.getPointerSize(200);
155 uint64_t PtrCpyAlign = DL.getPointerPrefAlignment(200);
156 if ((Size > PtrCpySize) || (CopyDstAlign < PtrCpyAlign) ||
157 (CopySrcAlign < PtrCpyAlign))
158 return nullptr;
159 CpyTy = Type::getInt8PtrTy(MI->getContext(), 200);
160 }
161
162 // If it is an atomic and alignment is less than the size then we will
163 // introduce the unaligned memory access which will be later transformed
164 // into libcall in CodeGen. This is not evident performance gain so disable
165 // it now.
166 if (isa<AtomicMemTransferInst>(MI))
167 if (CopyDstAlign < Size || CopySrcAlign < Size)
168 return nullptr;
169
170 // Use an integer load+store unless we can find something better.
171 unsigned SrcAddrSp =
172 cast<PointerType>(MI->getArgOperand(1)->getType())->getAddressSpace();
173 unsigned DstAddrSp =
174 cast<PointerType>(MI->getArgOperand(0)->getType())->getAddressSpace();
175
176 if (!CpyTy)
177 CpyTy = IntegerType::get(MI->getContext(), Size<<3);
178 Type *NewSrcPtrTy = PointerType::get(CpyTy, SrcAddrSp);
179 Type *NewDstPtrTy = PointerType::get(CpyTy, DstAddrSp);
180
181 // If the memcpy has metadata describing the members, see if we can get the
182 // TBAA tag describing our copy.
183 MDNode *CopyMD = nullptr;
184 if (MDNode *M = MI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_tbaa)) {
185 CopyMD = M;
186 } else if (MDNode *M = MI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_tbaa_struct)) {
187 if (M->getNumOperands() == 3 && M->getOperand(0) &&
188 mdconst::hasa<ConstantInt>(M->getOperand(0)) &&
189 mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(M->getOperand(0))->isZero() &&
190 M->getOperand(1) &&
191 mdconst::hasa<ConstantInt>(M->getOperand(1)) &&
192 mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(M->getOperand(1))->getValue() ==
193 Size &&
194 M->getOperand(2) && isa<MDNode>(M->getOperand(2)))
195 CopyMD = cast<MDNode>(M->getOperand(2));
196 }
197
198 Value *Src = Builder.CreateBitCast(MI->getArgOperand(1), NewSrcPtrTy);
199 Value *Dest = Builder.CreateBitCast(MI->getArgOperand(0), NewDstPtrTy);
200 LoadInst *L = Builder.CreateLoad(CpyTy, Src);
201 // Alignment from the mem intrinsic will be better, so use it.
202 L->setAlignment(CopySrcAlign);
203 if (CopyMD)
204 L->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_tbaa, CopyMD);
205 MDNode *LoopMemParallelMD =
206 MI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_mem_parallel_loop_access);
207 if (LoopMemParallelMD)
208 L->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_mem_parallel_loop_access, LoopMemParallelMD);
209 MDNode *AccessGroupMD = MI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_access_group);
210 if (AccessGroupMD)
211 L->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_access_group, AccessGroupMD);
212
213 StoreInst *S = Builder.CreateStore(L, Dest);
214 // Alignment from the mem intrinsic will be better, so use it.
215 S->setAlignment(CopyDstAlign);
216 if (CopyMD)
217 S->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_tbaa, CopyMD);
218 if (LoopMemParallelMD)
219 S->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_mem_parallel_loop_access, LoopMemParallelMD);
220 if (AccessGroupMD)
221 S->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_access_group, AccessGroupMD);
222
223 if (auto *MT = dyn_cast<MemTransferInst>(MI)) {
224 // non-atomics can be volatile
225 L->setVolatile(MT->isVolatile());
226 S->setVolatile(MT->isVolatile());
227 }
228 if (isa<AtomicMemTransferInst>(MI)) {
229 // atomics have to be unordered
230 L->setOrdering(AtomicOrdering::Unordered);
231 S->setOrdering(AtomicOrdering::Unordered);
232 }
233
234 // Set the size of the copy to 0, it will be deleted on the next iteration.
235 MI->setLength(Constant::getNullValue(MemOpLength->getType()));
236 return MI;
237}

239Instruction *InstCombiner::SimplifyAnyMemSet(AnyMemSetInst *MI) {
240 unsigned Alignment = getKnownAlignment(MI->getDest(), DL, MI, &AC, &DT);
241 if (MI->getDestAlignment() < Alignment) {
242 MI->setDestAlignment(Alignment);
243 return MI;
244 }
245
246 // If we have a store to a location which is known constant, we can conclude
247 // that the store must be storing the constant value (else the memory
248 // wouldn't be constant), and this must be a noop.
249 if (AA->pointsToConstantMemory(MI->getDest())) {
250 // Set the size of the copy to 0, it will be deleted on the next iteration.
251 MI->setLength(Constant::getNullValue(MI->getLength()->getType()));
252 return MI;
253 }
254
255 // Extract the length and alignment and fill if they are constant.
256 ConstantInt *LenC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(MI->getLength());
257 ConstantInt *FillC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(MI->getValue());
258 if (!LenC || !FillC || !FillC->getType()->isIntegerTy(8))
259 return nullptr;
260 uint64_t Len = LenC->getLimitedValue();
261 Alignment = MI->getDestAlignment();
262 assert(Len && "0-sized memory setting should be removed already.");
263
264 // Alignment 0 is identity for alignment 1 for memset, but not store.
265 if (Alignment == 0)
266 Alignment = 1;
267
268 // If it is an atomic and alignment is less than the size then we will
269 // introduce the unaligned memory access which will be later transformed
270 // into libcall in CodeGen. This is not evident performance gain so disable
271 // it now.
272 if (isa<AtomicMemSetInst>(MI))
273 if (Alignment < Len)
274 return nullptr;
275
276 // memset(s,c,n) -> store s, c (for n=1,2,4,8)
277 if (Len <= 8 && isPowerOf2_32((uint32_t)Len)) {
278 Type *ITy = IntegerType::get(MI->getContext(), Len*8); // n=1 -> i8.
279
280 Value *Dest = MI->getDest();
281 unsigned DstAddrSp = cast<PointerType>(Dest->getType())->getAddressSpace();
282 Type *NewDstPtrTy = PointerType::get(ITy, DstAddrSp);
283 Dest = Builder.CreateBitCast(Dest, NewDstPtrTy);
284
285 // Extract the fill value and store.
286 uint64_t Fill = FillC->getZExtValue()*0x0101010101010101ULL;
287 StoreInst *S = Builder.CreateStore(ConstantInt::get(ITy, Fill), Dest,
288 MI->isVolatile());
289 S->setAlignment(Alignment);
290 if (isa<AtomicMemSetInst>(MI))
291 S->setOrdering(AtomicOrdering::Unordered);
292
293 // Set the size of the copy to 0, it will be deleted on the next iteration.
294 MI->setLength(Constant::getNullValue(LenC->getType()));
295 return MI;
296 }
297
298 return nullptr;
299}

301static Value *simplifyX86immShift(const IntrinsicInst &II,
302 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
303 bool LogicalShift = false;
304 bool ShiftLeft = false;
305
306 switch (II.getIntrinsicID()) {
307 default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected intrinsic!");
308 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psra_d:
309 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psra_w:
310 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrai_d:
311 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrai_w:
312 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psra_d:
313 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psra_w:
314 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrai_d:
315 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrai_w:
316 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psra_q_128:
317 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrai_q_128:
318 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psra_q_256:
319 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrai_q_256:
320 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psra_d_512:
321 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psra_q_512:
322 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psra_w_512:
323 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrai_d_512:
324 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrai_q_512:
325 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrai_w_512:
326 LogicalShift = false; ShiftLeft = false;
327 break;
328 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrl_d:
329 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrl_q:
330 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrl_w:
331 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrli_d:
332 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrli_q:
333 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psrli_w:
334 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrl_d:
335 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrl_q:
336 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrl_w:
337 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrli_d:
338 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrli_q:
339 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrli_w:
340 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrl_d_512:
341 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrl_q_512:
342 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrl_w_512:
343 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrli_d_512:
344 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrli_q_512:
345 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrli_w_512:
346 LogicalShift = true; ShiftLeft = false;
347 break;
348 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psll_d:
349 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psll_q:
350 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_psll_w:
351 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_pslli_d:
352 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_pslli_q:
353 case Intrinsic::x86_sse2_pslli_w:
354 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psll_d:
355 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psll_q:
356 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psll_w:
357 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_pslli_d:
358 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_pslli_q:
359 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_pslli_w:
360 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psll_d_512:
361 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psll_q_512:
362 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psll_w_512:
363 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_pslli_d_512:
364 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_pslli_q_512:
365 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_pslli_w_512:
366 LogicalShift = true; ShiftLeft = true;
367 break;
368 }
369 assert((LogicalShift || !ShiftLeft) && "Only logical shifts can shift left");
370
371 // Simplify if count is constant.
372 auto Arg1 = II.getArgOperand(1);
373 auto CAZ = dyn_cast<ConstantAggregateZero>(Arg1);
374 auto CDV = dyn_cast<ConstantDataVector>(Arg1);
375 auto CInt = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Arg1);
376 if (!CAZ && !CDV && !CInt)
377 return nullptr;
378
379 APInt Count(64, 0);
380 if (CDV) {
381 // SSE2/AVX2 uses all the first 64-bits of the 128-bit vector
382 // operand to compute the shift amount.
383 auto VT = cast<VectorType>(CDV->getType());
384 unsigned BitWidth = VT->getElementType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits();
385 assert((64 % BitWidth) == 0 && "Unexpected packed shift size");
386 unsigned NumSubElts = 64 / BitWidth;
387
388 // Concatenate the sub-elements to create the 64-bit value.
389 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumSubElts; ++i) {
390 unsigned SubEltIdx = (NumSubElts - 1) - i;
391 auto SubElt = cast<ConstantInt>(CDV->getElementAsConstant(SubEltIdx));
392 Count <<= BitWidth;
393 Count |= SubElt->getValue().zextOrTrunc(64);
394 }
395 }
396 else if (CInt)
397 Count = CInt->getValue();
398
399 auto Vec = II.getArgOperand(0);
400 auto VT = cast<VectorType>(Vec->getType());
401 auto SVT = VT->getElementType();
402 unsigned VWidth = VT->getNumElements();
403 unsigned BitWidth = SVT->getPrimitiveSizeInBits();
404
405 // If shift-by-zero then just return the original value.
406 if (Count.isNullValue())
407 return Vec;
408
409 // Handle cases when Shift >= BitWidth.
410 if (Count.uge(BitWidth)) {
411 // If LogicalShift - just return zero.
412 if (LogicalShift)
413 return ConstantAggregateZero::get(VT);
414
415 // If ArithmeticShift - clamp Shift to (BitWidth - 1).
416 Count = APInt(64, BitWidth - 1);
417 }
418
419 // Get a constant vector of the same type as the first operand.
420 auto ShiftAmt = ConstantInt::get(SVT, Count.zextOrTrunc(BitWidth));
421 auto ShiftVec = Builder.CreateVectorSplat(VWidth, ShiftAmt);
422
423 if (ShiftLeft)
424 return Builder.CreateShl(Vec, ShiftVec);
425
426 if (LogicalShift)
427 return Builder.CreateLShr(Vec, ShiftVec);
428
429 return Builder.CreateAShr(Vec, ShiftVec);
430}

432// Attempt to simplify AVX2 per-element shift intrinsics to a generic IR shift.
433// Unlike the generic IR shifts, the intrinsics have defined behaviour for out
434// of range shift amounts (logical - set to zero, arithmetic - splat sign bit).
435static Value *simplifyX86varShift(const IntrinsicInst &II,
436 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
437 bool LogicalShift = false;
438 bool ShiftLeft = false;
439
440 switch (II.getIntrinsicID()) {
441 default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected intrinsic!");
442 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrav_d:
443 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrav_d_256:
444 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_q_128:
445 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_q_256:
446 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_d_512:
447 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_q_512:
448 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_w_128:
449 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_w_256:
450 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrav_w_512:
451 LogicalShift = false;
452 ShiftLeft = false;
453 break;
454 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrlv_d:
455 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrlv_d_256:
456 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrlv_q:
457 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psrlv_q_256:
458 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrlv_d_512:
459 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrlv_q_512:
460 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrlv_w_128:
461 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrlv_w_256:
462 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psrlv_w_512:
463 LogicalShift = true;
464 ShiftLeft = false;
465 break;
466 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psllv_d:
467 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psllv_d_256:
468 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psllv_q:
469 case Intrinsic::x86_avx2_psllv_q_256:
470 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psllv_d_512:
471 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psllv_q_512:
472 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psllv_w_128:
473 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psllv_w_256:
474 case Intrinsic::x86_avx512_psllv_w_512:
475 LogicalShift = true;
476 ShiftLeft = true;
477 break;
478 }
479 assert((LogicalShift || !ShiftLeft) && "Only logical shifts can shift left");
480
481 // Simplify if all shift amounts are constant/undef.
482 auto *CShift = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(1));
483 if (!CShift)
484 return nullptr;
485
486 auto Vec = II.getArgOperand(0);
487 auto VT = cast<VectorType>(II.getType());
488 auto SVT = VT->getVectorElementType();
489 int NumElts = VT->getNumElements();
490 int BitWidth = SVT->getIntegerBitWidth();
491
492 // Collect each element's shift amount.
493 // We also collect special cases: UNDEF = -1, OUT-OF-RANGE = BitWidth.
494 bool AnyOutOfRange = false;
495 SmallVector<int, 8> ShiftAmts;
496 for (int I = 0; I < NumElts; ++I) {
497 auto *CElt = CShift->getAggregateElement(I);
498 if (CElt && isa<UndefValue>(CElt)) {
499 ShiftAmts.push_back(-1);
500 continue;
501 }
502
503 auto *COp = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(CElt);
504 if (!COp)
505 return nullptr;
506
507 // Handle out of range shifts.
508 // If LogicalShift - set to BitWidth (special case).
509 // If ArithmeticShift - set to (BitWidth - 1) (sign splat).
510 APInt ShiftVal = COp->getValue();
511 if (ShiftVal.uge(BitWidth)) {
512 AnyOutOfRange = LogicalShift;
513 ShiftAmts.push_back(LogicalShift ? BitWidth : BitWidth - 1);
514 continue;
515 }
516
517 ShiftAmts.push_back((int)ShiftVal.getZExtValue());
518 }
519
520 // If all elements out of range or UNDEF, return vector of zeros/undefs.
521 // ArithmeticShift should only hit this if they are all UNDEF.
522 auto OutOfRange = [&](int Idx) { return (Idx < 0) || (BitWidth <= Idx); };
523 if (llvm::all_of(ShiftAmts, OutOfRange)) {
524 SmallVector<Constant *, 8> ConstantVec;
525 for (int Idx : ShiftAmts) {
526 if (Idx < 0) {
527 ConstantVec.push_back(UndefValue::get(SVT));
528 } else {
529 assert(LogicalShift && "Logical shift expected");
530 ConstantVec.push_back(ConstantInt::getNullValue(SVT));
531 }
532 }
533 return ConstantVector::get(ConstantVec);
534 }
535
536 // We can't handle only some out of range values with generic logical shifts.
537 if (AnyOutOfRange)
538 return nullptr;
539
540 // Build the shift amount constant vector.
541 SmallVector<Constant *, 8> ShiftVecAmts;
542 for (int Idx : ShiftAmts) {
543 if (Idx < 0)
544 ShiftVecAmts.push_back(UndefValue::get(SVT));
545 else
546 ShiftVecAmts.push_back(ConstantInt::get(SVT, Idx));
547 }
548 auto ShiftVec = ConstantVector::get(ShiftVecAmts);
549
550 if (ShiftLeft)
551 return Builder.CreateShl(Vec, ShiftVec);
552
553 if (LogicalShift)
554 return Builder.CreateLShr(Vec, ShiftVec);
555
556 return Builder.CreateAShr(Vec, ShiftVec);
557}

559static Value *simplifyX86pack(IntrinsicInst &II,
560 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder, bool IsSigned) {
561 Value *Arg0 = II.getArgOperand(0);
562 Value *Arg1 = II.getArgOperand(1);
563 Type *ResTy = II.getType();
564
565 // Fast all undef handling.
566 if (isa<UndefValue>(Arg0) && isa<UndefValue>(Arg1))
567 return UndefValue::get(ResTy);
568
569 Type *ArgTy = Arg0->getType();
570 unsigned NumLanes = ResTy->getPrimitiveSizeInBits() / 128;
571 unsigned NumSrcElts = ArgTy->getVectorNumElements();
572 assert(ResTy->getVectorNumElements() == (2 * NumSrcElts) &&
573 "Unexpected packing types");
574
575 unsigned NumSrcEltsPerLane = NumSrcElts / NumLanes;
576 unsigned DstScalarSizeInBits = ResTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
577 unsigned SrcScalarSizeInBits = ArgTy->getScalarSizeInBits();
578 assert(SrcScalarSizeInBits == (2 * DstScalarSizeInBits) &&
579 "Unexpected packing types");
580
581 // Constant folding.
582 if (!isa<Constant>(Arg0) || !isa<Constant>(Arg1))
583 return nullptr;
584
585 // Clamp Values - signed/unsigned both use signed clamp values, but they
586 // differ on the min/max values.
587 APInt MinValue, MaxValue;
588 if (IsSigned) {
589 // PACKSS: Truncate signed value with signed saturation.
590 // Source values less than dst minint are saturated to minint.
591 // Source values greater than dst maxint are saturated to maxint.
592 MinValue =
593 APInt::getSignedMinValue(DstScalarSizeInBits).sext(SrcScalarSizeInBits);
594 MaxValue =
595 APInt::getSignedMaxValue(DstScalarSizeInBits).sext(SrcScalarSizeInBits);
596 } else {
597 // PACKUS: Truncate signed value with unsigned saturation.
598 // Source values less than zero are saturated to zero.
599 // Source values greater than dst maxuint are saturated to maxuint.
600 MinValue = APInt::getNullValue(SrcScalarSizeInBits);
601 MaxValue = APInt::getLowBitsSet(SrcScalarSizeInBits, DstScalarSizeInBits);
602 }
603
604 auto *MinC = Constant::getIntegerValue(ArgTy, MinValue);
605 auto *MaxC = Constant::getIntegerValue(ArgTy, MaxValue);
606 Arg0 = Builder.CreateSelect(Builder.CreateICmpSLT(Arg0, MinC), MinC, Arg0);
607 Arg1 = Builder.CreateSelect(Builder.CreateICmpSLT(Arg1, MinC), MinC, Arg1);
608 Arg0 = Builder.CreateSelect(Builder.CreateICmpSGT(Arg0, MaxC), MaxC, Arg0);
609 Arg1 = Builder.CreateSelect(Builder.CreateICmpSGT(Arg1, MaxC), MaxC, Arg1);
610
611 // Shuffle clamped args together at the lane level.
612 SmallVector<unsigned, 32> PackMask;
613 for (unsigned Lane = 0; Lane != NumLanes; ++Lane) {
614 for (unsigned Elt = 0; Elt != NumSrcEltsPerLane; ++Elt)
615 PackMask.push_back(Elt + (Lane * NumSrcEltsPerLane));
616 for (unsigned Elt = 0; Elt != NumSrcEltsPerLane; ++Elt)
617 PackMask.push_back(Elt + (Lane * NumSrcEltsPerLane) + NumSrcElts);
618 }
619 auto *Shuffle = Builder.CreateShuffleVector(Arg0, Arg1, PackMask);
620
621 // Truncate to dst size.
622 return Builder.CreateTrunc(Shuffle, ResTy);
623}

625static Value *simplifyX86movmsk(const IntrinsicInst &II,
626 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
627 Value *Arg = II.getArgOperand(0);
628 Type *ResTy = II.getType();
629 Type *ArgTy = Arg->getType();
630
631 // movmsk(undef) -> zero as we must ensure the upper bits are zero.
632 if (isa<UndefValue>(Arg))
633 return Constant::getNullValue(ResTy);
634
635 // We can't easily peek through x86_mmx types.
636 if (!ArgTy->isVectorTy())
637 return nullptr;
638
639 // Expand MOVMSK to compare/bitcast/zext:
640 // e.g. PMOVMSKB(v16i8 x):
641 // %cmp = icmp slt <16 x i8> %x, zeroinitializer
642 // %int = bitcast <16 x i1> %cmp to i16
643 // %res = zext i16 %int to i32
644 unsigned NumElts = ArgTy->getVectorNumElements();
645 Type *IntegerVecTy = VectorType::getInteger(cast<VectorType>(ArgTy));
646 Type *IntegerTy = Builder.getIntNTy(NumElts);
647
648 Value *Res = Builder.CreateBitCast(Arg, IntegerVecTy);
649 Res = Builder.CreateICmpSLT(Res, Constant::getNullValue(IntegerVecTy));
650 Res = Builder.CreateBitCast(Res, IntegerTy);
651 Res = Builder.CreateZExtOrTrunc(Res, ResTy);
652 return Res;
653}

655static Value *simplifyX86addcarry(const IntrinsicInst &II,
656 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
657 Value *CarryIn = II.getArgOperand(0);
658 Value *Op1 = II.getArgOperand(1);
659 Value *Op2 = II.getArgOperand(2);
660 Type *RetTy = II.getType();
661 Type *OpTy = Op1->getType();
662 assert(RetTy->getStructElementType(0)->isIntegerTy(8) &&
663 RetTy->getStructElementType(1) == OpTy && OpTy == Op2->getType() &&
664 "Unexpected types for x86 addcarry");
665
666 // If carry-in is zero, this is just an unsigned add with overflow.
667 if (match(CarryIn, m_ZeroInt())) {
668 Value *UAdd = Builder.CreateIntrinsic(Intrinsic::uadd_with_overflow, OpTy,
669 { Op1, Op2 });
670 // The types have to be adjusted to match the x86 call types.
671 Value *UAddResult = Builder.CreateExtractValue(UAdd, 0);
672 Value *UAddOV = Builder.CreateZExt(Builder.CreateExtractValue(UAdd, 1),
673 Builder.getInt8Ty());
674 Value *Res = UndefValue::get(RetTy);
675 Res = Builder.CreateInsertValue(Res, UAddOV, 0);
676 return Builder.CreateInsertValue(Res, UAddResult, 1);
677 }
678
679 return nullptr;
680}

682static Value *simplifyX86insertps(const IntrinsicInst &II,
683 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
684 auto *CInt = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(II.getArgOperand(2));
685 if (!CInt)
686 return nullptr;
687
688 VectorType *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(II.getType());
689 assert(VecTy->getNumElements() == 4 && "insertps with wrong vector type");
690
691 // The immediate permute control byte looks like this:
692 // [3:0] - zero mask for each 32-bit lane
693 // [5:4] - select one 32-bit destination lane
694 // [7:6] - select one 32-bit source lane
695
696 uint8_t Imm = CInt->getZExtValue();
697 uint8_t ZMask = Imm & 0xf;
698 uint8_t DestLane = (Imm >> 4) & 0x3;
699 uint8_t SourceLane = (Imm >> 6) & 0x3;
700
701 ConstantAggregateZero *ZeroVector = ConstantAggregateZero::get(VecTy);
702
703 // If all zero mask bits are set, this was just a weird way to
704 // generate a zero vector.
705 if (ZMask == 0xf)
706 return ZeroVector;
707
708 // Initialize by passing all of the first source bits through.
709 uint32_t ShuffleMask[4] = { 0, 1, 2, 3 };
710
711 // We may replace the second operand with the zero vector.
712 Value *V1 = II.getArgOperand(1);
713
714 if (ZMask) {
715 // If the zero mask is being used with a single input or the zero mask
716 // overrides the destination lane, this is a shuffle with the zero vector.
717 if ((II.getArgOperand(0) == II.getArgOperand(1)) ||
718 (ZMask & (1 << DestLane))) {
719 V1 = ZeroVector;
720 // We may still move 32-bits of the first source vector from one lane
721 // to another.
722 ShuffleMask[DestLane] = SourceLane;
723 // The zero mask may override the previous insert operation.
724 for (unsigned i = 0; i < 4; ++i)
725 if ((ZMask >> i) & 0x1)
726 ShuffleMask[i] = i + 4;
727 } else {
728 // TODO: Model this case as 2 shuffles or a 'logical and' plus shuffle?
729 return nullptr;
730 }
731 } else {
732 // Replace the selected destination lane with the selected source lane.
733 ShuffleMask[DestLane] = SourceLane + 4;
734 }
735
736 return Builder.CreateShuffleVector(II.getArgOperand(0), V1, ShuffleMask);
737}

739/// Attempt to simplify SSE4A EXTRQ/EXTRQI instructions using constant folding
740/// or conversion to a shuffle vector.
741static Value *simplifyX86extrq(IntrinsicInst &II, Value *Op0,
742 ConstantInt *CILength, ConstantInt *CIIndex,
743 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
744 auto LowConstantHighUndef = [&](uint64_t Val) {
745 Type *IntTy64 = Type::getInt64Ty(II.getContext());
746 Constant *Args[] = {ConstantInt::get(IntTy64, Val),
747 UndefValue::get(IntTy64)};
748 return ConstantVector::get(Args);
749 };
750
751 // See if we're dealing with constant values.
752 Constant *C0 = dyn_cast<Constant>(Op0);
753 ConstantInt *CI0 =
754 C0 ? dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(C0->getAggregateElement((unsigned)0))
755 : nullptr;
756
757 // Attempt to constant fold.
758 if (CILength && CIIndex) {
759 // From AMD documentation: "The bit index and field length are each six
760 // bits in length other bits of the field are ignored."
761 APInt APIndex = CIIndex->getValue().zextOrTrunc(6);
762 APInt APLength = CILength->getValue().zextOrTrunc(6);
763
764 unsigned Index = APIndex.getZExtValue();
765
766 // From AMD documentation: "a value of zero in the field length is
767 // defined as length of 64".
768 unsigned Length = APLength == 0 ? 64 : APLength.getZExtValue();
769
770 // From AMD documentation: "If the sum of the bit index + length field
771 // is greater than 64, the results are undefined".
772 unsigned End = Index + Length;
773
774 // Note that both field index and field length are 8-bit quantities.
775 // Since variables 'Index' and 'Length' are unsigned values
776 // obtained from zero-extending field index and field length
777 // respectively, their sum should never wrap around.
778 if (End > 64)
779 return UndefValue::get(II.getType());
780
781 // If we are inserting whole bytes, we can convert this to a shuffle.
782 // Lowering can recognize EXTRQI shuffle masks.
783 if ((Length % 8) == 0 && (Index % 8) == 0) {
784 // Convert bit indices to byte indices.
785 Length /= 8;
786 Index /= 8;
787
788 Type *IntTy8 = Type::getInt8Ty(II.getContext());
789 Type *IntTy32 = Type::getInt32Ty(II.getContext());
790 VectorType *ShufTy = VectorType::get(IntTy8, 16);
791
792 SmallVector<Constant *, 16> ShuffleMask;
793 for (int i = 0; i != (int)Length; ++i)
794 ShuffleMask.push_back(
795 Constant::getIntegerValue(IntTy32, APInt(32, i + Index)));
796 for (int i = Length; i != 8; ++i)
797 ShuffleMask.push_back(
798 Constant::getIntegerValue(IntTy32, APInt(32, i + 16)));
799 for (int i = 8; i != 16; ++i)
800 ShuffleMask.push_back(UndefValue::get(IntTy32));
801
802 Value *SV = Builder.CreateShuffleVector(
803 Builder.CreateBitCast(Op0, ShufTy),
804 ConstantAggregateZero::get(ShufTy), ConstantVector::get(ShuffleMask));
805 return Builder.CreateBitCast(SV, II.getType());
806 }
807
808 // Constant Fold - shift Index'th bit to lowest position and mask off
809 // Length bits.
810 if (CI0) {
811 APInt Elt = CI0->getValue();
812 Elt.lshrInPlace(Index);
813 Elt = Elt.zextOrTrunc(Length);
814 return LowConstantHighUndef(Elt.getZExtValue());
815 }
816
817 // If we were an EXTRQ call, we'll save registers if we convert to EXTRQI.
818 if (II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::x86_sse4a_extrq) {
819 Value *Args[] = {Op0, CILength, CIIndex};
820 Module *M = II.getModule();
821 Function *F = Intrinsic::getDeclaration(M, Intrinsic::x86_sse4a_extrqi);
822 return Builder.CreateCall(F, Args);
823 }
824 }
825
826 // Constant Fold - extraction from zero is always {zero, undef}.
827 if (CI0 && CI0->isZero())
828 return LowConstantHighUndef(0);
829
830 return nullptr;
831}
832
833/// Attempt to simplify SSE4A INSERTQ/INSERTQI instructions using constant
834/// folding or conversion to a shuffle vector.
835static Value *simplifyX86insertq(IntrinsicInst &II, Value *Op0, Value *Op1,
836 APInt APLength, APInt APIndex,
837 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
838 // From AMD documentation: "The bit index and field length are each six bits
839 // in length other bits of the field are ignored."
840 APIndex = APIndex.zextOrTrunc(6);
841 APLength = APLength.zextOrTrunc(6);
842
843 // Attempt to constant fold.
844 unsigned Index = APIndex.getZExtValue();
845
846 // From AMD documentation: "a value of zero in the field length is
847 // defined as length of 64".
848 unsigned Length = APLength == 0 ? 64 : APLength.getZExtValue();
849
850 // From AMD documentation: "If the sum of the bit index + length field
851 // is greater than 64, the results are undefined".
852 unsigned End = Index + Length;
853
854 // Note that both field index and field length are 8-bit quantities.
855 // Since variables 'Index' and 'Length' are unsigned values
856 // obtained from zero-extending field index and field length
857 // respectively, their sum should never wrap around.
858 if (End > 64)
859 return UndefValue::get(II.getType());
860
861 // If we are inserting whole bytes, we can convert this to a shuffle.
862 // Lowering can recognize INSERTQI shuffle masks.
863 if ((Length % 8) == 0 && (Index % 8) == 0) {
864 // Convert bit indices to byte indices.
865 Length /= 8;
866 Index /= 8;
867
868 Type *IntTy8 = Type::getInt8Ty(II.getContext());
869 Type *IntTy32 = Type::getInt32Ty(II.getContext());
870 VectorType *ShufTy = VectorType::get(IntTy8, 16);
871
872 SmallVector<Constant *, 16> ShuffleMask;
873 for (int i = 0; i != (int)Index; ++i)
874 ShuffleMask.push_back(Constant::getIntegerValue(IntTy32, APInt(32, i)));
875 for (int i = 0; i != (int)Length; ++i)
876 ShuffleMask.push_back(
877 Constant::getIntegerValue(IntTy32, APInt(32, i + 16)));
878 for (int i = Index + Length; i != 8; ++i)
879 ShuffleMask.push_back(Constant::getIntegerValue(IntTy32, APInt(32, i)));
880 for (int i = 8; i != 16; ++i)
881 ShuffleMask.push_back(UndefValue::get(IntTy32));
882
883 Value *SV = Builder.CreateShuffleVector(Builder.CreateBitCast(Op0, ShufTy),
884 Builder.CreateBitCast(Op1, ShufTy),
885 ConstantVector::get(ShuffleMask));
886 return Builder.CreateBitCast(SV, II.getType());
887 }
888
889 // See if we're dealing with constant values.
890 Constant *C0 = dyn_cast<Constant>(Op0);
891 Constant *C1 = dyn_cast<Constant>(Op1);
892 ConstantInt *CI00 =
893 C0 ? dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(C0->getAggregateElement((unsigned)0))
894 : nullptr;
895 ConstantInt *CI10 =
896 C1 ? dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(C1->getAggregateElement((unsigned)0))
897 : nullptr;
898
899 // Constant Fold - insert bottom Length bits starting at the Index'th bit.
900 if (CI00 && CI10) {
901 APInt V00 = CI00->getValue();
902 APInt V10 = CI10->getValue();
903 APInt Mask = APInt::getLowBitsSet(64, Length).shl(Index);
904 V00 = V00 & ~Mask;
905 V10 = V10.zextOrTrunc(Length).zextOrTrunc(64).shl(Index);
906 APInt Val = V00 | V10;
907 Type *IntTy64 = Type::getInt64Ty(II.getContext());
908 Constant *Args[] = {ConstantInt::get(IntTy64, Val.getZExtValue()),
909 UndefValue::get(IntTy64)};
910 return ConstantVector::get(Args);
911 }
912
913 // If we were an INSERTQ call, we'll save demanded elements if we convert to
914 // INSERTQI.
915 if (II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::x86_sse4a_insertq) {
916 Type *IntTy8 = Type::getInt8Ty(II.getContext());
917 Constant *CILength = ConstantInt::get(IntTy8, Length, false);
918 Constant *CIIndex = ConstantInt::get(IntTy8, Index, false);
919
920 Value *Args[] = {Op0, Op1, CILength, CIIndex};
921 Module *M = II.getModule();
922 Function *F = Intrinsic::getDeclaration(M, Intrinsic::x86_sse4a_insertqi);
923 return Builder.CreateCall(F, Args);
924 }
925
926 return nullptr;
927}

929/// Attempt to convert pshufb* to shufflevector if the mask is constant.
930static Value *simplifyX86pshufb(const IntrinsicInst &II,
931 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
932 Constant *V = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(1));
933 if (!V)
934 return nullptr;
935
936 auto *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(II.getType());
937 auto *MaskEltTy = Type::getInt32Ty(II.getContext());
938 unsigned NumElts = VecTy->getNumElements();
939 assert((NumElts == 16 || NumElts == 32 || NumElts == 64) &&
940 "Unexpected number of elements in shuffle mask!");
941
942 // Construct a shuffle mask from constant integers or UNDEFs.
943 Constant *Indexes[64] = {nullptr};
944
945 // Each byte in the shuffle control mask forms an index to permute the
946 // corresponding byte in the destination operand.
947 for (unsigned I = 0; I < NumElts; ++I) {
948 Constant *COp = V->getAggregateElement(I);
949 if (!COp || (!isa<UndefValue>(COp) && !isa<ConstantInt>(COp)))
950 return nullptr;
951
952 if (isa<UndefValue>(COp)) {
953 Indexes[I] = UndefValue::get(MaskEltTy);
954 continue;
955 }
956
957 int8_t Index = cast<ConstantInt>(COp)->getValue().getZExtValue();
958
959 // If the most significant bit (bit[7]) of each byte of the shuffle
960 // control mask is set, then zero is written in the result byte.
961 // The zero vector is in the right-hand side of the resulting
962 // shufflevector.
963
964 // The value of each index for the high 128-bit lane is the least
965 // significant 4 bits of the respective shuffle control byte.
966 Index = ((Index < 0) ? NumElts : Index & 0x0F) + (I & 0xF0);
967 Indexes[I] = ConstantInt::get(MaskEltTy, Index);
968 }
969
970 auto ShuffleMask = ConstantVector::get(makeArrayRef(Indexes, NumElts));
971 auto V1 = II.getArgOperand(0);
972 auto V2 = Constant::getNullValue(VecTy);
973 return Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, V2, ShuffleMask);
974}

976/// Attempt to convert vpermilvar* to shufflevector if the mask is constant.
977static Value *simplifyX86vpermilvar(const IntrinsicInst &II,
978 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
979 Constant *V = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(1));
980 if (!V)
981 return nullptr;
982
983 auto *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(II.getType());
984 auto *MaskEltTy = Type::getInt32Ty(II.getContext());
985 unsigned NumElts = VecTy->getVectorNumElements();
986 bool IsPD = VecTy->getScalarType()->isDoubleTy();
987 unsigned NumLaneElts = IsPD ? 2 : 4;
988 assert(NumElts == 16 || NumElts == 8 || NumElts == 4 || NumElts == 2);
989
990 // Construct a shuffle mask from constant integers or UNDEFs.
991 Constant *Indexes[16] = {nullptr};
992
993 // The intrinsics only read one or two bits, clear the rest.
994 for (unsigned I = 0; I < NumElts; ++I) {
995 Constant *COp = V->getAggregateElement(I);
996 if (!COp || (!isa<UndefValue>(COp) && !isa<ConstantInt>(COp)))
997 return nullptr;
998
999 if (isa<UndefValue>(COp)) {
1000 Indexes[I] = UndefValue::get(MaskEltTy);
1001 continue;
1002 }
1003
1004 APInt Index = cast<ConstantInt>(COp)->getValue();
1005 Index = Index.zextOrTrunc(32).getLoBits(2);
1006
1007 // The PD variants uses bit 1 to select per-lane element index, so
1008 // shift down to convert to generic shuffle mask index.
1009 if (IsPD)
1010 Index.lshrInPlace(1);
1011
1012 // The _256 variants are a bit trickier since the mask bits always index
1013 // into the corresponding 128 half. In order to convert to a generic
1014 // shuffle, we have to make that explicit.
1015 Index += APInt(32, (I / NumLaneElts) * NumLaneElts);
1016
1017 Indexes[I] = ConstantInt::get(MaskEltTy, Index);
1018 }
1019
1020 auto ShuffleMask = ConstantVector::get(makeArrayRef(Indexes, NumElts));
1021 auto V1 = II.getArgOperand(0);
1022 auto V2 = UndefValue::get(V1->getType());
1023 return Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, V2, ShuffleMask);
1024}

1026/// Attempt to convert vpermd/vpermps to shufflevector if the mask is constant.
1027static Value *simplifyX86vpermv(const IntrinsicInst &II,
1028 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
1029 auto *V = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(1));
1030 if (!V)
1031 return nullptr;
1032
1033 auto *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(II.getType());
1034 auto *MaskEltTy = Type::getInt32Ty(II.getContext());
1035 unsigned Size = VecTy->getNumElements();
1036 assert((Size == 4 || Size == 8 || Size == 16 || Size == 32 || Size == 64) &&
1037 "Unexpected shuffle mask size");
1038
1039 // Construct a shuffle mask from constant integers or UNDEFs.
1040 Constant *Indexes[64] = {nullptr};
1041
1042 for (unsigned I = 0; I < Size; ++I) {
1043 Constant *COp = V->getAggregateElement(I);
1044 if (!COp || (!isa<UndefValue>(COp) && !isa<ConstantInt>(COp)))
1045 return nullptr;
1046
1047 if (isa<UndefValue>(COp)) {
1048 Indexes[I] = UndefValue::get(MaskEltTy);
1049 continue;
1050 }
1051
1052 uint32_t Index = cast<ConstantInt>(COp)->getZExtValue();
1053 Index &= Size - 1;
1054 Indexes[I] = ConstantInt::get(MaskEltTy, Index);
1055 }
1056
1057 auto ShuffleMask = ConstantVector::get(makeArrayRef(Indexes, Size));
1058 auto V1 = II.getArgOperand(0);

1060 return Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, V2, ShuffleMask);

1089// * Single constant active lane -> store

1091Instruction *InstCombiner::simplifyMaskedStore(IntrinsicInst &II) {
1092 auto *ConstMask = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(3));
1093 if (!ConstMask)
1094 return nullptr;

1096 // If the mask is all zeros, this instruction does nothing.
1097 if (ConstMask->isNullValue())
1098 return eraseInstFromFunction(II);
1099
1100 // If the mask is all ones, this is a plain vector store of the 1st argument.
1101 if (ConstMask->isAllOnesValue()) {
1102 Value *StorePtr = II.getArgOperand(1);

1104 return new StoreInst(II.getArgOperand(0), StorePtr, false, Alignment);

1108 APInt DemandedElts = possiblyDemandedEltsInMask(ConstMask);
1109 APInt UndefElts(DemandedElts.getBitWidth(), 0);
1110 if (Value *V = SimplifyDemandedVectorElts(II.getOperand(0),
1111 DemandedElts, UndefElts)) {
1112 II.setOperand(0, V);
1113 return &II;
1114 }
1115
1116 return nullptr;
1117}

1136Instruction *InstCombiner::simplifyMaskedScatter(IntrinsicInst &II) {
1137 auto *ConstMask = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(3));

1139 return nullptr;

1142 if (ConstMask->isNullValue())

1145 // Use masked off lanes to simplify operands via SimplifyDemandedVectorElts
1146 APInt DemandedElts = possiblyDemandedEltsInMask(ConstMask);
1147 APInt UndefElts(DemandedElts.getBitWidth(), 0);
1148 if (Value *V = SimplifyDemandedVectorElts(II.getOperand(0),
1149 DemandedElts, UndefElts)) {
1150 II.setOperand(0, V);
1151 return &II;
1152 }
1153 if (Value *V = SimplifyDemandedVectorElts(II.getOperand(1),
1154 DemandedElts, UndefElts)) {
1155 II.setOperand(1, V);
1156 return &II;
1157 }
1158
1159 return nullptr;
1160}
1161
1162/// This function transforms launder.invariant.group and strip.invariant.group
1163/// like:
1164/// launder(launder(%x)) -> launder(%x) (the result is not the argument)
1165/// launder(strip(%x)) -> launder(%x)
1166/// strip(strip(%x)) -> strip(%x) (the result is not the argument)
1167/// strip(launder(%x)) -> strip(%x)
1168/// This is legal because it preserves the most recent information about
1169/// the presence or absence of invariant.group.
1170static Instruction *simplifyInvariantGroupIntrinsic(IntrinsicInst &II,
1171 InstCombiner &IC) {
1172 auto *Arg = II.getArgOperand(0);
1173 auto *StrippedArg = Arg->stripPointerCasts();
1174 auto *StrippedInvariantGroupsArg = Arg->stripPointerCastsAndInvariantGroups();
1175 if (StrippedArg == StrippedInvariantGroupsArg)
1176 return nullptr; // No launders/strips to remove.
1177
1178 Value *Result = nullptr;
1179
1180 if (II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::launder_invariant_group)
1181 Result = IC.Builder.CreateLaunderInvariantGroup(StrippedInvariantGroupsArg);
1182 else if (II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::strip_invariant_group)
1183 Result = IC.Builder.CreateStripInvariantGroup(StrippedInvariantGroupsArg);
1184 else
1185 llvm_unreachable(
1186 "simplifyInvariantGroupIntrinsic only handles launder and strip");
1187 if (Result->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace() !=
1188 II.getType()->getPointerAddressSpace())
1189 Result = IC.Builder.CreateAddrSpaceCast(Result, II.getType());
1190 if (Result->getType() != II.getType())
1191 Result = IC.Builder.CreateBitCast(Result, II.getType());
1192
1193 return cast<Instruction>(Result);
1194}

1196static Instruction *foldCttzCtlz(IntrinsicInst &II, InstCombiner &IC) {
1197 assert((II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::cttz ||
1198 II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::ctlz) &&
1199 "Expected cttz or ctlz intrinsic");
1200 bool IsTZ = II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::cttz;
1201 Value *Op0 = II.getArgOperand(0);
1202 Value *X;
1203 // ctlz(bitreverse(x)) -> cttz(x)
1204 // cttz(bitreverse(x)) -> ctlz(x)
1205 if (match(Op0, m_BitReverse(m_Value(X)))) {
1206 Intrinsic::ID ID = IsTZ ? Intrinsic::ctlz : Intrinsic::cttz;
1207 Function *F = Intrinsic::getDeclaration(II.getModule(), ID, II.getType());
1208 return CallInst::Create(F, {X, II.getArgOperand(1)});
1209 }
1210
1211 KnownBits Known = IC.computeKnownBits(Op0, 0, &II);
1212
1213 // Create a mask for bits above (ctlz) or below (cttz) the first known one.
1214 unsigned PossibleZeros = IsTZ ? Known.countMaxTrailingZeros()
1215 : Known.countMaxLeadingZeros();
1216 unsigned DefiniteZeros = IsTZ ? Known.countMinTrailingZeros()
1217 : Known.countMinLeadingZeros();
1218
1219 // If all bits above (ctlz) or below (cttz) the first known one are known
1220 // zero, this value is constant.
1221 // FIXME: This should be in InstSimplify because we're replacing an
1222 // instruction with a constant.
1223 if (PossibleZeros == DefiniteZeros) {
1224 auto *C = ConstantInt::get(Op0->getType(), DefiniteZeros);
1225 return IC.replaceInstUsesWith(II, C);
1226 }
1227
1228 // If the input to cttz/ctlz is known to be non-zero,
1229 // then change the 'ZeroIsUndef' parameter to 'true'
1230 // because we know the zero behavior can't affect the result.
1231 if (!Known.One.isNullValue() ||
1232 isKnownNonZero(Op0, IC.getDataLayout(), 0, &IC.getAssumptionCache(), &II,
1233 &IC.getDominatorTree())) {
1234 if (!match(II.getArgOperand(1), m_One())) {
1235 II.setOperand(1, IC.Builder.getTrue());
1236 return &II;
1237 }
1238 }
1239
1240 // Add range metadata since known bits can't completely reflect what we know.
1241 // TODO: Handle splat vectors.
1242 auto *IT = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(Op0->getType());
1243 if (IT && IT->getBitWidth() != 1 && !II.getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {
1244 Metadata *LowAndHigh[] = {
1245 ConstantAsMetadata::get(ConstantInt::get(IT, DefiniteZeros)),
1246 ConstantAsMetadata::get(ConstantInt::get(IT, PossibleZeros + 1))};
1247 II.setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range,
1248 MDNode::get(II.getContext(), LowAndHigh));
1249 return &II;
1250 }
1251
1252 return nullptr;
1253}
1254
1255static Instruction *foldCtpop(IntrinsicInst &II, InstCombiner &IC) {
1256 assert(II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::ctpop &&
1257 "Expected ctpop intrinsic");
1258 Value *Op0 = II.getArgOperand(0);
1259 Value *X;
1260 // ctpop(bitreverse(x)) -> ctpop(x)
1261 // ctpop(bswap(x)) -> ctpop(x)
1262 if (match(Op0, m_BitReverse(m_Value(X))) || match(Op0, m_BSwap(m_Value(X)))) {
1263 II.setOperand(0, X);
1264 return &II;
1265 }
1266
1267 // FIXME: Try to simplify vectors of integers.
1268 auto *IT = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(Op0->getType());
1269 if (!IT)
1270 return nullptr;
1271
1272 unsigned BitWidth = IT->getBitWidth();
1273 KnownBits Known(BitWidth);
1274 IC.computeKnownBits(Op0, Known, 0, &II);
1275
1276 unsigned MinCount = Known.countMinPopulation();
1277 unsigned MaxCount = Known.countMaxPopulation();
1278
1279 // Add range metadata since known bits can't completely reflect what we know.
1280 if (IT->getBitWidth() != 1 && !II.getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) {
1281 Metadata *LowAndHigh[] = {
1282 ConstantAsMetadata::get(ConstantInt::get(IT, MinCount)),
1283 ConstantAsMetadata::get(ConstantInt::get(IT, MaxCount + 1))};
1284 II.setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range,
1285 MDNode::get(II.getContext(), LowAndHigh));
1286 return &II;
1287 }
1288
1289 return nullptr;
1290}

1292// TODO: If the x86 backend knew how to convert a bool vector mask back to an
1293// XMM register mask efficiently, we could transform all x86 masked intrinsics
1294// to LLVM masked intrinsics and remove the x86 masked intrinsic defs.
1295static Instruction *simplifyX86MaskedLoad(IntrinsicInst &II, InstCombiner &IC) {
1296 Value *Ptr = II.getOperand(0);
1297 Value *Mask = II.getOperand(1);
1298 Constant *ZeroVec = Constant::getNullValue(II.getType());
1299
1300 // Special case a zero mask since that's not a ConstantDataVector.
1301 // This masked load instruction creates a zero vector.
1302 if (isa<ConstantAggregateZero>(Mask))
1303 return IC.replaceInstUsesWith(II, ZeroVec);
1304
1305 auto *ConstMask = dyn_cast<ConstantDataVector>(Mask);
1306 if (!ConstMask)
1307 return nullptr;
1308
1309 // The mask is constant. Convert this x86 intrinsic to the LLVM instrinsic
1310 // to allow target-independent optimizations.
1311
1312 // First, cast the x86 intrinsic scalar pointer to a vector pointer to match
1313 // the LLVM intrinsic definition for the pointer argument.
1314 unsigned AddrSpace = cast<PointerType>(Ptr->getType())->getAddressSpace();
1315 PointerType *VecPtrTy = PointerType::get(II.getType(), AddrSpace);
1316 Value *PtrCast = IC.Builder.CreateBitCast(Ptr, VecPtrTy, "castvec");
1317
1318 // Second, convert the x86 XMM integer vector mask to a vector of bools based
1319 // on each element's most significant bit (the sign bit).
1320 Constant *BoolMask = getNegativeIsTrueBoolVec(ConstMask);
1321
1322 // The pass-through vector for an x86 masked load is a zero vector.
1323 CallInst *NewMaskedLoad =
1324 IC.Builder.CreateMaskedLoad(PtrCast, 1, BoolMask, ZeroVec);
1325 return IC.replaceInstUsesWith(II, NewMaskedLoad);
1326}
1327
1328// TODO: If the x86 backend knew how to convert a bool vector mask back to an
1329// XMM register mask efficiently, we could transform all x86 masked intrinsics
1330// to LLVM masked intrinsics and remove the x86 masked intrinsic defs.
1331static bool simplifyX86MaskedStore(IntrinsicInst &II, InstCombiner &IC) {
1332 Value *Ptr = II.getOperand(0);
1333 Value *Mask = II.getOperand(1);
1334 Value *Vec = II.getOperand(2);
1335
1336 // Special case a zero mask since that's not a ConstantDataVector:
1337 // this masked store instruction does nothing.
1338 if (isa<ConstantAggregateZero>(Mask)) {
1339 IC.eraseInstFromFunction(II);
1340 return true;
1341 }
1342
1343 // The SSE2 version is too weird (eg, unaligned but non-temporal) to do
1344 // anything else at this level.
1345 if (II.getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::x86_sse2_maskmov_dqu)
1346 return false;
1347
1348 auto *ConstMask = dyn_cast<ConstantDataVector>(Mask);
1349 if (!ConstMask)
1350 return false;
1351
1352 // The mask is constant. Convert this x86 intrinsic to the LLVM instrinsic
1353 // to allow target-independent optimizations.
1354
1355 // First, cast the x86 intrinsic scalar pointer to a vector pointer to match
1356 // the LLVM intrinsic definition for the pointer argument.
1357 unsigned AddrSpace = cast<PointerType>(Ptr->getType())->getAddressSpace();
1358 PointerType *VecPtrTy = PointerType::get(Vec->getType(), AddrSpace);
1359 Value *PtrCast = IC.Builder.CreateBitCast(Ptr, VecPtrTy, "castvec");
1360
1361 // Second, convert the x86 XMM integer vector mask to a vector of bools based
1362 // on each element's most significant bit (the sign bit).
1363 Constant *BoolMask = getNegativeIsTrueBoolVec(ConstMask);
1364
1365 IC.Builder.CreateMaskedStore(Vec, PtrCast, 1, BoolMask);
1366
1367 // 'Replace uses' doesn't work for stores. Erase the original masked store.
1368 IC.eraseInstFromFunction(II);
1369 return true;
1370}
1371
1372// Constant fold llvm.amdgcn.fmed3 intrinsics for standard inputs.
1373//
1374// A single NaN input is folded to minnum, so we rely on that folding for
1375// handling NaNs.
1376static APFloat fmed3AMDGCN(const APFloat &Src0, const APFloat &Src1,
1377 const APFloat &Src2) {
1378 APFloat Max3 = maxnum(maxnum(Src0, Src1), Src2);
1379
1380 APFloat::cmpResult Cmp0 = Max3.compare(Src0);
1381 assert(Cmp0 != APFloat::cmpUnordered && "nans handled separately");
1382 if (Cmp0 == APFloat::cmpEqual)
1383 return maxnum(Src1, Src2);
1384
1385 APFloat::cmpResult Cmp1 = Max3.compare(Src1);
1386 assert(Cmp1 != APFloat::cmpUnordered && "nans handled separately");
1387 if (Cmp1 == APFloat::cmpEqual)
1388 return maxnum(Src0, Src2);
1389
1390 return maxnum(Src0, Src1);
1391}

1393/// Convert a table lookup to shufflevector if the mask is constant.
1394/// This could benefit tbl1 if the mask is { 7,6,5,4,3,2,1,0 }, in
1395/// which case we could lower the shufflevector with rev64 instructions
1396/// as it's actually a byte reverse.
1397static Value *simplifyNeonTbl1(const IntrinsicInst &II,
1398 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
1399 // Bail out if the mask is not a constant.
1400 auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(II.getArgOperand(1));
1401 if (!C)
1402 return nullptr;
1403
1404 auto *VecTy = cast<VectorType>(II.getType());
1405 unsigned NumElts = VecTy->getNumElements();
1406
1407 // Only perform this transformation for <8 x i8> vector types.
1408 if (!VecTy->getElementType()->isIntegerTy(8) || NumElts != 8)
1409 return nullptr;
1410
1411 uint32_t Indexes[8];
1412
1413 for (unsigned I = 0; I < NumElts; ++I) {
1414 Constant *COp = C->getAggregateElement(I);
1415
1416 if (!COp || !isa<ConstantInt>(COp))
1417 return nullptr;
1418
1419 Indexes[I] = cast<ConstantInt>(COp)->getLimitedValue();
1420
1421 // Make sure the mask indices are in range.
1422 if (Indexes[I] >= NumElts)
1423 return nullptr;
1424 }
1425
1426 auto *ShuffleMask = ConstantDataVector::get(II.getContext(),
1427 makeArrayRef(Indexes));
1428 auto *V1 = II.getArgOperand(0);
1429 auto *V2 = Constant::getNullValue(V1->getType());
1430 return Builder.CreateShuffleVector(V1, V2, ShuffleMask);
1431}

1433/// Convert a vector load intrinsic into a simple llvm load instruction.
1434/// This is beneficial when the underlying object being addressed comes
1435/// from a constant, since we get constant-folding for free.
1436static Value *simplifyNeonVld1(const IntrinsicInst &II,
1437 unsigned MemAlign,
1438 InstCombiner::BuilderTy &Builder) {
1439 auto *IntrAlign = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(II.getArgOperand(1));
1440
1441 if (!IntrAlign)
1442 return nullptr;
1443
1444 unsigned Alignment = IntrAlign->getLimitedValue() < MemAlign ?
1445 MemAlign : IntrAlign->getLimitedValue();
1446
1447 if (!isPowerOf2_32(Alignment))
1448 return nullptr;
1449
1450 auto *BCastInst = Builder.CreateBitCast(II.getArgOperand(0),
1451 PointerType::get(II.getType(), 0));
1452 return Builder.CreateAlignedLoad(II.getType(), BCastInst, Alignment);
1453}

1455// Returns true iff the 2 intrinsics have the same operands, limiting the
1456// comparison to the first NumOperands.
1457static bool haveSameOperands(const IntrinsicInst &I, const IntrinsicInst &E,
1458 unsigned NumOperands) {
1459 assert(I.getNumArgOperands() >= NumOperands && "Not enough operands");
1460 assert(E.getNumArgOperands() >= NumOperands && "Not enough operands");
1461 for (unsigned i = 0; i < NumOperands; i++)
1462 if (I.getArgOperand(i) != E.getArgOperand(i))
1463 return false;
1464 return true;
1465}
1466
1467// Remove trivially empty start/end intrinsic ranges, i.e. a start
1468// immediately followed by an end (ignoring debuginfo or other
1469// start/end intrinsics in between). As this handles only the most trivial
1470// cases, tracking the nesting level is not needed:
1471//
1472// call @llvm.foo.start(i1 0) ; &I
1473// call @llvm.foo.start(i1 0)
1474// call @llvm.foo.end(i1 0) ; This one will not be skipped: it will be removed
1475// call @llvm.foo.end(i1 0)
1476static bool removeTriviallyEmptyRange(IntrinsicInst &I, unsigned StartID,
1477 unsigned EndID, InstCombiner &IC) {
1478 assert(I.getIntrinsicID() == StartID &&
1479 "Start intrinsic does not have expected ID");
1480 BasicBlock::iterator BI(I), BE(I.getParent()->end());
1481 for (++BI; BI != BE; ++BI) {
1482 if (auto *E = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(BI)) {
1483 if (isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(E) || E->getIntrinsicID() == StartID)
1484 continue;
1485 if (E->getIntrinsicID() == EndID &&
1486 haveSameOperands(I, *E, E->getNumArgOperands())) {
1487 IC.eraseInstFromFunction(*E);
1488 IC.eraseInstFromFunction(I);
1489 return true;
1490 }
1491 }
1492 break;
1493 }
1494
1495 return false;
1496}

1498// Convert NVVM intrinsics to target-generic LLVM code where possible.
1499static Instruction *SimplifyNVVMIntrinsic(IntrinsicInst *II, InstCombiner &IC) {
1500 // Each NVVM intrinsic we can simplify can be replaced with one of:
1501 //
1502 // * an LLVM intrinsic,
1503 // * an LLVM cast operation,
1504 // * an LLVM binary operation, or
1505 // * ad-hoc LLVM IR for the particular operation.
1506
1507 // Some transformations are only valid when the module's
1508 // flush-denormals-to-zero (ftz) setting is true/false, whereas other
1509 // transformations are valid regardless of the module's ftz setting.
1510 enum FtzRequirementTy {
1511 FTZ_Any, // Any ftz setting is ok.
1512 FTZ_MustBeOn, // Transformation is valid only if ftz is on.
1513 FTZ_MustBeOff, // Transformation is valid only if ftz is off.
1514 };
1515 // Classes of NVVM intrinsics that can't be replaced one-to-one with a
1516 // target-generic intrinsic, cast op, or binary op but that we can nonetheless
1517 // simplify.
1518 enum SpecialCase {
1519 SPC_Reciprocal,
1520 };
1521
1522 // SimplifyAction is a poor-man's variant (plus an additional flag) that
1523 // represents how to replace an NVVM intrinsic with target-generic LLVM IR.
1524 struct SimplifyAction {
1525 // Invariant: At most one of these Optionals has a value.
1526 Optional<Intrinsic::ID> IID;
1527 Optional<Instruction::CastOps> CastOp;
1528 Optional<Instruction::BinaryOps> BinaryOp;
1529 Optional<SpecialCase> Special;
1530
1531 FtzRequirementTy FtzRequirement = FTZ_Any;
1532
1533 SimplifyAction() = default;
1534
1535 SimplifyAction(Intrinsic::ID IID, FtzRequirementTy FtzReq)
1536 : IID(IID), FtzRequirement(FtzReq) {}
1537
1538 // Cast operations don't have anything to do with FTZ, so we skip that
1539 // argument.
1540 SimplifyAction(Instruction::CastOps CastOp) : CastOp(CastOp) {}
1541
1542 SimplifyAction(Instruction::BinaryOps BinaryOp, FtzRequirementTy FtzReq)
1543 : BinaryOp(BinaryOp), FtzRequirement(FtzReq) {}
1544
1545 SimplifyAction(SpecialCase Special, FtzRequirementTy FtzReq)
1546 : Special(Special), FtzRequirement(FtzReq) {}
1547 };
1548
1549 // Try to generate a SimplifyAction describing how to replace our
1550 // IntrinsicInstr with target-generic LLVM IR.
1551 const SimplifyAction Action = [II]() -> SimplifyAction {
1552 switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
1553 // NVVM intrinsics that map directly to LLVM intrinsics.
1554 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ceil_d:
1555 return {Intrinsic::ceil, FTZ_Any};
1556 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ceil_f:
1557 return {Intrinsic::ceil, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1558 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ceil_ftz_f:
1559 return {Intrinsic::ceil, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1560 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fabs_d:
1561 return {Intrinsic::fabs, FTZ_Any};
1562 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fabs_f:
1563 return {Intrinsic::fabs, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1564 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fabs_ftz_f:
1565 return {Intrinsic::fabs, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1566 case Intrinsic::nvvm_floor_d:
1567 return {Intrinsic::floor, FTZ_Any};
1568 case Intrinsic::nvvm_floor_f:
1569 return {Intrinsic::floor, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1570 case Intrinsic::nvvm_floor_ftz_f:
1571 return {Intrinsic::floor, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1572 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fma_rn_d:
1573 return {Intrinsic::fma, FTZ_Any};
1574 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fma_rn_f:
1575 return {Intrinsic::fma, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1576 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fma_rn_ftz_f:
1577 return {Intrinsic::fma, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1578 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fmax_d:
1579 return {Intrinsic::maxnum, FTZ_Any};
1580 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fmax_f:
1581 return {Intrinsic::maxnum, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1582 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fmax_ftz_f:
1583 return {Intrinsic::maxnum, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1584 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fmin_d:
1585 return {Intrinsic::minnum, FTZ_Any};
1586 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fmin_f:
1587 return {Intrinsic::minnum, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1588 case Intrinsic::nvvm_fmin_ftz_f:
1589 return {Intrinsic::minnum, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1590 case Intrinsic::nvvm_round_d:
1591 return {Intrinsic::round, FTZ_Any};
1592 case Intrinsic::nvvm_round_f:
1593 return {Intrinsic::round, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1594 case Intrinsic::nvvm_round_ftz_f:
1595 return {Intrinsic::round, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1596 case Intrinsic::nvvm_sqrt_rn_d:
1597 return {Intrinsic::sqrt, FTZ_Any};
1598 case Intrinsic::nvvm_sqrt_f:
1599 // nvvm_sqrt_f is a special case. For most intrinsics, foo_ftz_f is the
1600 // ftz version, and foo_f is the non-ftz version. But nvvm_sqrt_f adopts
1601 // the ftz-ness of the surrounding code. sqrt_rn_f and sqrt_rn_ftz_f are
1602 // the versions with explicit ftz-ness.
1603 return {Intrinsic::sqrt, FTZ_Any};
1604 case Intrinsic::nvvm_sqrt_rn_f:
1605 return {Intrinsic::sqrt, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1606 case Intrinsic::nvvm_sqrt_rn_ftz_f:
1607 return {Intrinsic::sqrt, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1608 case Intrinsic::nvvm_trunc_d:
1609 return {Intrinsic::trunc, FTZ_Any};
1610 case Intrinsic::nvvm_trunc_f:
1611 return {Intrinsic::trunc, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1612 case Intrinsic::nvvm_trunc_ftz_f:
1613 return {Intrinsic::trunc, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1614
1615 // NVVM intrinsics that map to LLVM cast operations.
1616 //
1617 // Note that llvm's target-generic conversion operators correspond to the rz
1618 // (round to zero) versions of the nvvm conversion intrinsics, even though
1619 // most everything else here uses the rn (round to nearest even) nvvm ops.
1620 case Intrinsic::nvvm_d2i_rz:
1621 case Intrinsic::nvvm_f2i_rz:
1622 case Intrinsic::nvvm_d2ll_rz:
1623 case Intrinsic::nvvm_f2ll_rz:
1624 return {Instruction::FPToSI};
1625 case Intrinsic::nvvm_d2ui_rz:
1626 case Intrinsic::nvvm_f2ui_rz:
1627 case Intrinsic::nvvm_d2ull_rz:
1628 case Intrinsic::nvvm_f2ull_rz:
1629 return {Instruction::FPToUI};
1630 case Intrinsic::nvvm_i2d_rz:
1631 case Intrinsic::nvvm_i2f_rz:
1632 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ll2d_rz:
1633 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ll2f_rz:
1634 return {Instruction::SIToFP};
1635 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ui2d_rz:
1636 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ui2f_rz:
1637 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ull2d_rz:
1638 case Intrinsic::nvvm_ull2f_rz:
1639 return {Instruction::UIToFP};
1640
1641 // NVVM intrinsics that map to LLVM binary ops.
1642 case Intrinsic::nvvm_add_rn_d:
1643 return {Instruction::FAdd, FTZ_Any};
1644 case Intrinsic::nvvm_add_rn_f:
1645 return {Instruction::FAdd, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1646 case Intrinsic::nvvm_add_rn_ftz_f:
1647 return {Instruction::FAdd, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1648 case Intrinsic::nvvm_mul_rn_d:
1649 return {Instruction::FMul, FTZ_Any};
1650 case Intrinsic::nvvm_mul_rn_f:
1651 return {Instruction::FMul, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1652 case Intrinsic::nvvm_mul_rn_ftz_f:
1653 return {Instruction::FMul, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1654 case Intrinsic::nvvm_div_rn_d:
1655 return {Instruction::FDiv, FTZ_Any};
1656 case Intrinsic::nvvm_div_rn_f:
1657 return {Instruction::FDiv, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1658 case Intrinsic::nvvm_div_rn_ftz_f:
1659 return {Instruction::FDiv, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1660
1661 // The remainder of cases are NVVM intrinsics that map to LLVM idioms, but
1662 // need special handling.
1663 //
1664 // We seem to be missing intrinsics for rcp.approx.{ftz.}f32, which is just
1665 // as well.
1666 case Intrinsic::nvvm_rcp_rn_d:
1667 return {SPC_Reciprocal, FTZ_Any};
1668 case Intrinsic::nvvm_rcp_rn_f:
1669 return {SPC_Reciprocal, FTZ_MustBeOff};
1670 case Intrinsic::nvvm_rcp_rn_ftz_f:
1671 return {SPC_Reciprocal, FTZ_MustBeOn};
1672
1673 // We do not currently simplify intrinsics that give an approximate answer.
1674 // These include:
1675 //
1676 // - nvvm_cos_approx_{f,ftz_f}
1677 // - nvvm_ex2_approx_{d,f,ftz_f}
1678 // - nvvm_lg2_approx_{d,f,ftz_f}
1679 // - nvvm_sin_approx_{f,ftz_f}
1680 // - nvvm_sqrt_approx_{f,ftz_f}
1681 // - nvvm_rsqrt_approx_{d,f,ftz_f}
1682 // - nvvm_div_approx_{ftz_d,ftz_f,f}
1683 // - nvvm_rcp_approx_ftz_d
1684 //
1685 // Ideally we'd encode them as e.g. "fast call @llvm.cos", where "fast"
1686 // means that fastmath is enabled in the intrinsic. Unfortunately only
1687 // binary operators (currently) have a fastmath bit in SelectionDAG, so this
1688 // information gets lost and we can't select on it.
1689 //
1690 // TODO: div and rcp are lowered to a binary op, so these we could in theory
1691 // lower them to "fast fdiv".
1692
1693 default:
1694 return {};
1695 }
1696 }();
1697
1698 // If Action.FtzRequirementTy is not satisfied by the module's ftz state, we
1699 // can bail out now. (Notice that in the case that IID is not an NVVM
1700 // intrinsic, we don't have to look up any module metadata, as
1701 // FtzRequirementTy will be FTZ_Any.)
1702 if (Action.FtzRequirement != FTZ_Any) {
1703 bool FtzEnabled =
1704 II->getFunction()->getFnAttribute("nvptx-f32ftz").getValueAsString() ==
1705 "true";
1706
1707 if (FtzEnabled != (Action.FtzRequirement == FTZ_MustBeOn))
1708 return nullptr;
1709 }
1710
1711 // Simplify to target-generic intrinsic.
1712 if (Action.IID) {
1713 SmallVector<Value *, 4> Args(II->arg_operands());
1714 // All the target-generic intrinsics currently of interest to us have one
1715 // type argument, equal to that of the nvvm intrinsic's argument.
1716 Type *Tys[] = {II->getArgOperand(0)->getType()};
1717 return CallInst::Create(
1718 Intrinsic::getDeclaration(II->getModule(), *Action.IID, Tys), Args);
1719 }
1720
1721 // Simplify to target-generic binary op.
1722 if (Action.BinaryOp)
1723 return BinaryOperator::Create(*Action.BinaryOp, II->getArgOperand(0),
1724 II->getArgOperand(1), II->getName());
1725
1726 // Simplify to target-generic cast op.
1727 if (Action.CastOp)
1728 return CastInst::Create(*Action.CastOp, II->getArgOperand(0), II->getType(),
1729 II->getName());
1730
1731 // All that's left are the special cases.
1732 if (!Action.Special)
1733 return nullptr;
1734
1735 switch (*Action.Special) {
1736 case SPC_Reciprocal:
1737 // Simplify reciprocal.
1738 return BinaryOperator::Create(
1739 Instruction::FDiv, ConstantFP::get(II->getArgOperand(0)->getType(), 1),
1740 II->getArgOperand(0), II->getName());
1741 }
1742 llvm_unreachable("All SpecialCase enumerators should be handled in switch.");
1743}
1744
1745Instruction *InstCombiner::visitVAStartInst(VAStartInst &I) {
1746 removeTriviallyEmptyRange(I, Intrinsic::vastart, Intrinsic::vaend, *this);
1747 return nullptr;
1748}
1749
1750Instruction *InstCombiner::visitVACopyInst(VACopyInst &I) {
1751 removeTriviallyEmptyRange(I, Intrinsic::vacopy, Intrinsic::vaend, *this);
1752 return nullptr;
1753}
